    <h1>Thai movies and munchies to check out | C3</h1>
    <h2>Miss week&#xAD;end trips to Bangkok? Es&#xAD;cape to the Land of Smiles through film, food and sport</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201222/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-22"><time>2020-12-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ben&#xAD;son Ang&#xD;&#xA;Life&#xAD;style Correspond&#xAD;ent bang@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>With cheap, mouth-wa­ter­ing food, gorgeous beaches and fun-lov­ing, ever-smil­ing lo­cals, it is no won­der Thai­land is one of Sin­ga­pore­ans’ favourite des­ti­na­tions to visit.</p>
    <p>In­stead of lament­ing when week­end Bangkok trips will be­come pos­si­ble again, try a bit of Thai op­ti­mism and re­cap­ture that bliss in Sin­ga­pore un­til your stash of baht comes in handy again.</p>
    <p>In any case, with tech­nol­ogy, you can still visit Thai­land – that is, vir­tu­ally.</p>
    <p>This year, the Tourism Author­ity of Thai­land launched vir­tual tours to some at­trac­tions in Bangkok, Chi­ang Mai, Phuket and Surat Thani (bit.ly/2JF4pJP), as well as prov­inces (bit.ly/2K9Nn64) such as Phrae and Lop­buri.</p>
    <p>My on­line tour of the Phi­mai His­tor­i­cal Park – one of Thai­land’s largest Kh­mer tem­ples, lo­cated in Nakhon Ratchasima prov­ince – was divine.</p>
    <p>I floated through the im­pres­sive sand­stone struc­tures, glanc­ing at the awe-in­spir­ing lo­tus-shaped roofs.</p>
    <p>Although the place was bathed in the scorch­ing mid­day sun, I re­mained sweat-free, nes­tled in my air-con­di­tioned room at home.</p>
    <p>• This is an oc­ca­sional col­umn on ex­pe­ri­enc­ing other coun­tries in Sin­ga­pore. For more sto­ries on ex­plor­ing Sin­ga­pore, go to str.sg/sg-go-where.</p>

